{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14854"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.03,0.03,0.06,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112913"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7545"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94945"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"3228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"5186"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112913"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with constant restlessness and an inability to sit still for the past three days. She has schizophrenia and was started on risperidone two weeks ago. She takes no other regular medications. She appears distressed and states she has an uncomfortable urge to keep moving. She denies any suicidal thoughts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears agitated with vital signs within normal limits. She is unable to remain seated during the consultation, frequently standing up and pacing. There is no rigidity or tremor. She has no fever or other neurological signs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tardive dyskinesia","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Acute dystonia","Akathisia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of antipsychotic-induced \u003Cstrong\u003Eakathisia\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by subjective feelings of inner restlessness and a compelling need to move. The timing of onset (two weeks after starting risperidone) and the presentation (inability to sit still, pacing) are typical. Akathisia is one of the most common extrapyramidal side effects of antipsychotic medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETardive dyskinesia\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops after months to years of antipsychotic use and presents with involuntary, repetitive movements of the face, tongue, and extremities. The recent onset and nature of symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute dystonia\u003C/strong\u003E usually occurs within days of starting an antipsychotic and presents with sustained muscle contractions causing twisting movements or abnormal postures, often affecting the neck, face, or tongue. The absence of muscle spasms or abnormal posturing makes this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe reaction characterised by hyperthermia, muscle rigidity, altered mental status, and autonomic dysfunction. The absence of fever, rigidity, and other systemic symptoms excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with autonomic instability, neuromuscular abnormalities, and mental status changes. It typically occurs with selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors or other serotonergic medications, not antipsychotics alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of akathisia typically involves reducing the antipsychotic dose if possible, switching to an alternative agent with lower risk, or adding medications such as propranolol. The condition can be very distressing and may affect medication adherence if not properly addressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Akathisia is characterised by a subjective feeling of inner restlessness and compelling need to move","Akathisia is a common side effect of antipsychotic medications, typically occurring within days to weeks of starting treatment","Management of antipsychotic-induced akathisia includes dose reduction, switching agents, or adding beta-blockers"],"references":["D\u0027Souza RS, Hooten WM. Extrapyramidal symptoms. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; updated 2023 Jul 31. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534115/","Kane JM, Fleischhacker WW, Hansen L, Perlis R, Pikalov A, Assun\u00e7\u00e3o-Talbott S, et al. Akathisia: an updated review focusing on second-generation antipsychotics. J Clin Psychiatry 2009;70:627-43. Available at: https://www.psychiatrist.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/10554_akathisia-updated-review-focusing-second-generation.pdf","Jethwa KD. Pharmacological management of antipsychotic-induced akathisia: an update and treatment algorithm. BJPsych Adv 2015;21:342-4. Available at: https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/bjpsych-advances/article/pharmacological-management-of-antipsychoticinduced-akathisia-an-update-and-treatment-algorithm/F9539508CAF512358754C6FD93BAF26D"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94945"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94945"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T03:13:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T03:14:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7545"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112913"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou